rnment/organisations/department-for-work-pensions"}],"roles":[{"api_path":"/api/content/government/ministers/secretary-of-state-for-work-and-pensions","base_path":"/government/ministers/secretary-of-state-for-work-and-pensions","content_id":"845e6272-c0f1-11e4-8223-005056011aef","document_type":"ministerial_role","locale":"en","public_updated_at":"2018-01-10T10:52:23Z","schema_name":"role","title":"Secretary of State for Work and Pensions","withdrawn":false,"details":{"body":"\u003cp\u003eThe Secretary of State has overall responsibility for the Department for Work and Pensions (\u003cabbr title=\"Department for Work and Pensions\"\u003eDWP\u003c/abbr\u003e). They have direct responsibility for departmental expenditure and departmental management.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cabbr title=\"Department for Work and Pensions\"\u003eDWP\u003c/abbr\u003e is responsible for the administration of the State Pension and working age benefits system, providing support to:\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cul\u003e\n  \u003cli\u003epeople of working age\u003c/li\u003e\n  \u003cli\u003eemployers\u003c/li\u003e\n  \u003cli\u003epensioners\u003c/li\u003e\n  \u003cli\u003efamilies and children\u003c/li\u003e\n  \u003cli\u003edisabled people\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n"},"links":{},"api_url":"https://www.gov.uk/api/content/government/ministers/secretary-of-state-for-work-and-pensions","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/government/ministers/secretary-of-state-for-work-and-pensions"}],"available_translations":[{"title":"Seven years in jail for bosses who recklessly risk pensions","public_updated_at":"2019-02-11T10:05:23Z","document_type":"press_release","schema_name":"news_article","base_path":"/government/news/seven-years-in-jail-for-bosses-who-recklessly-risk-pensions","api_path":"/api/content/government/news/seven-years-in-jail-for-bosses-who-recklessly-risk-pensions","withdrawn":false,"content_id":"ea18a6bd-1858-4ee3-9098-7163ad37e16c","locale":"en","api_url":"https://www.gov.uk/api/content/government/news/seven-years-in-jail-for-bosses-who-recklessly-risk-pensions","web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/government/news/seven-years-in-jail-for-bosses-who-recklessly-risk-pensions","links":{}}]},"description":"Devil-may-care directors who recklessly put workersâ€™ pensions at risk will face up to 7 years in prison or unlimited fines.","details":{"body":"\u003cp\u003eA new criminal offence of â€˜wilful or reckless behaviourâ€™ in relation to pensions will be introduced under the proposals to crack down on abuse of final or average salary schemes.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eSecretary of State for Work and Pensions Amber Rudd, said:\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cblockquote\u003e\n  \u003cp class=\"last-child\"\u003eThe vast majority of bosses take their responsibilities seriously and look after their workersâ€™ retirement funds.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e\n\n\u003cblockquote\u003e\n  \u003cp class=\"last-child\"\u003eHowever, for too long the reckless few playing fast and loose with peopleâ€™s futures have got away scot-free. Acts of astonishing arrogance and abandon punished only with fines, barely denting bossesâ€™ bank balances.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e\n\n\u003cblockquote\u003e\n  \u003cp class=\"last-child\"\u003eMeanwhile workers who have done the right thing and saved for retirement, confident their investments were safe, are left facing a leaner later life.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e\n\n\u003cblockquote\u003e\n  \u003cp class=\"last-child\"\u003eThat cannot be right, which is why, for the first time, weâ€™re going to make wilful or reckless behaviour relating to pensions a criminal offence.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eThe move is designed to ensure company bosses who allow deficits to escalate to unsustainable levels, or who endanger their workersâ€™ savings through chronic mismanagement, face the full force of the law.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eThe intention to introduce a new criminal offence of wilful or reckless behaviour in relation to a pension scheme, and the recommended maximum sentence, is included in the \u003ca href=\"https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/protecting-defined-benefit-pension-schemes-a-stronger-pensions-regulator\"\u003egovernmentâ€™s response to a consultation on enhancing The Pensions Regulatorâ€™s powers\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eIt comes as latest figures revealed more than 10 million people have been brought into workplace pensions saving by automatic enrolment since 2012.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eThe milestone confirms the success of the governmentâ€™s flagship policy requiring employers to enrol eligible workers into a workplace pension scheme.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eSecretary of State Amber Rudd, added:\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cblockquote\u003e\n  \u003cp class=\"last-child\"\u003eAutomatic enrolment is an extraordinary success story. Thanks to this revolutionary reform, 10 million people can look forward to a more secure future and a better retirement.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e\n\n\u003cblockquote\u003e\n  \u003cp class=\"last-child\"\u003eThat is a remarkable achievement. Workplace pensions had fallen out of fashion and were seen as the preserve of older, wealthier people. Now saving is the norm across the UK, wherever you work.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e\n\n\u003cblockquote\u003e\n  \u003cp class=\"last-child\"\u003eAs we reflect on this milestone, we will of course be considering how we can reach even more people â€“ with our ambition to bring in younger workers and enable everyone, particularly part-time and lower earners and the self-employed, to save more.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eMinimum contribution rates under automatic enrolment are due to rise from 5% to 8% in April, as part of the governmentâ€™s plans to help people save even more.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eAttitudes towards workplace pension saving are positive and, thanks to automatic enrolment, pension saving is becoming normal. Saving behaviour is sticking: the first increase in minimum contributions which took place last year has not prompted people to stop saving.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eThe proportion stopping saving through automatic enrolment was just 0.7% in the three months following the April 2018 increase in contribution rates, compared to 0.6% for the 4 year period beforehand.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eWith record numbers investing in their retirement, the government is introducing a number of additional protections for savers, including a new authorisation regime to govern trusts administering pensions.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eThe Department for Work and Pensions has already unveiled pioneering proposals to facilitate industry to deliver â€˜pensions dashboardsâ€™, providing all the facts and figures about someoneâ€™s pension savings in one place online.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch2 id=\"contact-press-office\"\u003eContact Press Office\u003c/h2\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eMedia enquiries for this press release â€“ 020 3267 5084\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cdiv id=\"contact_df0a78d2-6122-46ac-8014-6f8c5e0b8d3f\" class=\"contact postal-address\"\u003e\n  \u003cdiv class=\"content\"\u003e\n    \u003ch3\u003ePress Office\u003c/h3\u003e\n    \u003cdiv class=\"vcard contact-inner\"\u003e\n    \n      \u003cp class=\"adr\"\u003e\n\u003cspan class=\"street-address\"\u003eCaxton House\n\u003cbr\u003e\nTothill Street\u003c/span\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\n\u003cspan class=\"locality\"\u003eLondon\u003c/span\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\n\u003cspan class=\"postal-code\"\u003eSW1H 9NA\u003c/span\u003e\n\u003c/p\u003e\n\n    \n    \n      \u003cdiv class=\"email-url-number\"\u003e\n      \n      \n      \n        \u003cp class=\"tel\"\u003e\n          \u003cspan class=\"type\"\u003eLondon Press Office (national media and London area enquiries only â€“ not questions about personal claims)\u003c/span\u003e\n          020 3267 5144\n   